        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Of course. That was an excellent and cooperative effort. Your performance on that exam was flawless.\n\nThe results are all within normal limits: your cranial nerves are intact, your motor strength is symmetric and strong, your coordination is precise, and your gait, even with the heel-to-toe test, was steady.\n\nIt is an important and reassuring result. It means that from a neurological standpoint, there are no obvious red flags in the exam I just performed. It helps us rule out many serious neurological conditions.\n\nBut you are absolutely right to point out its limitation: the exam can only assess for gross or obvious neurological deficits. It cannot see what's happening inside. It cannot detect a small bleed, a tiny clot, an underlying infection, or an anomaly in the blood vessels themselves. That is what the CT scan of your head is for.\n\nSo while the exam is a crucial first step, the imaging is the critical next step to get us the definitive answers we need.\n\nThe team is ready for you now. Let's proceed with the CT scan."
