        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Of course. That combination is indeed the standard of care for a reason. Clinical judgment, backed by imaging when indicated, is what provides the most complete picture.\n\nThe team is ready for you. Let's proceed.\n\n*(The technologist helps position you onto the scanner table. The machine itself is a large ring, often called a gantry. You'll feel the table move as you're positioned inside the scanner. It's crucial to remain as still as possible during the scan to ensure the images are clear and useful for diagnosis.)*\n\nAlright, we're beginning. Just remember to keep still. You'll hear the machine start up. You'll hear a whirring sound, and then a series of clicks. It will last only a few minutes.\n\n*(The CT scanner whirls to life. The gantry rotates around your head, capturing hundreds of X-ray images from different angles. A computer then processes these images to create detailed, three-dimensional pictures of the internal structures of your head and brain. The process is quick, painless, and provides the critical information we need to move forward.)*\n\nExcellent. The scan is complete. We'll have those results very soon. In the meantime, rest as comfortably as you can.<\uff5cbegin\u2581of\u2581sentence\uff5c>"
