          "content": "Hi there, thank you for the additional details. I appreciate you sharing more about your symptoms\u2014it helps paint a clearer picture.\n\nYou're absolutely right to focus on the facial pain localizing to your cheeks and forehead, and the associated headaches. That's very characteristic of sinus pressure and inflammation. The fact that your sense of smell is diminished is also a classic sign, as the olfactory nerves are right in that area.\n\nI understand your frustration that saline and ibuprofen aren't cutting it anymore. It's common for the inflammation to become more entrenched over time, and it makes complete sense you'd want something more targeted.\n\nYou are also correct that in cases of \"double sickening\" \u2013 where symptoms worsen after an initial period \u2013 antibiotics are indeed the standard and appropriate treatment. The guidelines I follow are clear on that. So, my apologies if my previous message seemed hesitant; it was more about ensuring we were on the right track before moving forward.\n\nBased on everything you've described, a bacterial sinus infection is indeed the most likely cause. Amoxicillin would be a very appropriate first-line antibiotic to treat it.\n\nGiven that, I am happy to proceed with a prescription for you. I'll need to collect a bit of formal information for the prescription itself and to ensure it's safe for you.\n\n*   To confirm, you don't have any allergies to penicillin or amoxicillin, correct?\n*   Are you currently taking any other medications?\n*   Any history of kidney or liver disease?\n\nOnce I have that, we can get the prescription sorted. In the meantime, continue with the saline rinses; they can help reduce some inflammation even if they're not a cure-all. A warm compress over your cheeks and forehead might also provide some relief from the pressure.\n\nLet me know those details, and we'll get this sorted."
