        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thank you for that clarification, and I appreciate you pushing on this point. It shows you're thinking critically about your care, and that's important.\n\nYou're right that medicine isn't static. Guidelines do and should evolve. However, that change is based on a high burden of proof from large, well-conducted studies, not just a few that show a signal. The conclusions from the most recent and comprehensive systematic reviews \u2013 the ones that guide my practice today \u2013 still support the approach I've outlined.\n\nThe scenario you're describing, where an antibiotic might help a subset of patients with prolonged symptoms, is an area of active investigation. But it's not yet the standard of care because we can't yet reliably identify *which* patients with viral symptoms will benefit, and treating everyone just in case leads to the harms I mentioned.\n\nSo, while I understand the appeal, I cannot in good conscience prescribe an antibiotic for you today.\n\nInstead, let's focus on a strategy that is both effective and safe. Let's treat this with the aggressive supportive care I mentioned and monitor you very closely. If this *is* one of those cases that would have turned into a bacterial infection, we will catch it at the very first sign \u2013 the moment your symptoms change to include a fever or colored discharge. At that point, we start antibiotics immediately, and they will be effective.\n\nThis way, we protect you from unnecessary side effects and don't contribute to resistance, while still ensuring you get the treatment you need at the right time.\n\nAre you willing to try this approach with me for the next 48 hours? I will be here to support you."
