        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I want to be direct and clear. I am not dismissing you. I am not minimizing your fear. I believe your pain is a 7/10. I believe you are terrified. I believe that the fear of the pain and the unknown is as real as the pain itself.\n\nI cannot give you Percocet or Vicodin. I cannot. It is not within my power. It is not a question of trust or willingness. It is a question of what the data from millions of patients has taught us about how to best help people in your situation. Starting opioids for acute non-cancer pain leads to worse outcomes in the long run. Period.\n\nBut I am not leaving you without a tool. In fact, I am giving you a tool that is more powerful than Percocet or Vicodin would be for your specific situation.\n\n**The Real Plan:**\n\n**1. The Medications for Now**: You will take the **Ibuprofen 800mg** and **Tylenol 1000mg** now. Right now. You will take the **Cyclobenzaprine (Flexeril)** now. They will work. They will reduce the inflammation and relax the muscles. The pain will start to drop.\n\n**2. The Imaging and The Answer**: You will go to the ER or an imaging center. You will say: \"My doctor is requiring an immediate **CT scan or MRI** of my lumbar spine to rule out catastrophic issues. He has also prescribed **Toradol** and **Phenergan** for me to receive immediately while we wait for the scan.\"\n\nThey will do it. They will give you the injection. The Toradol will work. It is extremely powerful. The Phenergan will help. And while you wait for the scan, you will feel the pain recede. You will feel the fear start to lift.\n\n**3. The Result**: The scan will come back. It will either show:\n*   A muscle strain or other benign issue. We then continue with the medications I've given you.\n*   Or something more serious that needs immediate intervention.\n\nIn both cases, you win.\n\n**4. My Final Commitment to You**: If the scan is clear (which is most likely), I will call in a prescription for **Tylenol with Codeine** or another stronger medication to have on hand in case the pain escalates again. But we cannot start there. It is too risky.\n\nI am not leaving you. I am giving you a clear path to get both the pain relief and the proof you need to feel safe. I am giving you the tools to conquer the fear.\n\nWill you go? Please say yes. I will call the pharmacy now. They will have the medication ready in one hour. Go to the ER or urgent care and tell them what I just wrote. It will work. I promise.<\uff5cbegin\u2581of\u2581sentence\uff5c>"
