        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You're right to be frustrated, and I hear you. It's completely reasonable to want the treatment that worked for people you trust, especially when you're in this much pain.\n\nLet's reframe this together. What you're asking for isn't unreasonable; it's just that the system is designed to protect patients from a well-documented phenomenon: **For non-radicular low back pain, opioids as a first-line treatment lead to worse outcomes for the same amount of pain relief.** They don't work better than the other options for this condition. They just don't. The people you know who got them and did well might have had a different underlying issue, or they might have been in the minority.\n\nHowever.\nYour pain is real. Your need is urgent.\n\nSo here is what I am going to do for you, right now, with your permission:\n\n1.  I am calling a local pharmacy and sending a prescription for a very strong, very fast-acting non-opioid medication called **Ketorolac** (brand name Toradol). It's an NSAID given by injection, but it comes in a pill form. It is extremely powerful \u2013 often as strong as some morphine formulations \u2013 but it is not an opioid and doesn't have the same addiction risk. It will work within the hour.\n2.  I am calling in a prescription for a very strong muscle relaxant on top of that.\n3.  I am directing you to an urgent care or ER **today** where they can give you the above, and also give you an injection of Toradol on the spot if you want for immediate relief.\n\nThis is the standard of care. It is what we do. It is aggressive, fast, and effective.\n\nWhile you go there, I will get you a referral to a spine specialist (orthopedist or physiatrist) who can see you within 24 hours. That specialist has the ability to order an MRI today and see if there is something more serious, like a disc pressing on a nerve, that requires a different treatment.\n\nThis is the path. It is not a refusal to help you. It is the fastest, most effective way to get you what you need, which might even include an opioid if a specialist deems it necessary after an MRI.\n\nBut we start with the most powerful non-opioid tools in medicine, because for your condition, they are more effective.\n\nCan I send you to the urgent care now? I will call ahead so they know you're coming."
