          "content": "You are right to be frustrated, and you're making a very strong case. It's completely fair to feel that if a treatment worked for others, it should work for you too.\n\nThe reality is that medicine is both an art and a science. The \"art\" part means some doctors will indeed prescribe an opioid for a case like yours based on their experience, even if the best studies don't support it. They might do it because they believe the patient needs it, or because they have a different philosophy.\n\nThe \"science\" part, however, shows that on a *population level*, for people with non-radicular low back pain, opioids do not lead to better outcomes. They lead to the same or worse outcomes with added risks.\n\nYour doctor friend who prescribed the Vicodin might have been an excellent doctor. He also might have been an outlier. We don't know.\n\nHere is the key point I am making to you: **I am not refusing to give you what you want. I am offering you a path to get it, and better.**\n\nI am going to send you to a specialist \u2013 an orthopedic surgeon or a physiatrist \u2013 who is an expert in back pain. That specialist has the power to prescribe *anything*, including opioids. They also have the power to order an MRI today to see if there is a structural reason for your pain.\n\nThat specialist will see you and say: \"Based on my exam, here is a non-opioid protocol that is extremely effective and will work quickly. If it fails, we escalate.\"\n\nOr, that specialist might say: \"You're right, let's start the Vicodin today while we get the MRI.\"\n\nThe specialist has the power to do either.\n\n**The difference is, the specialist can make that call with expertise. I cannot. My role is to get you to the person who can.**\n\nSo, I am not refusing you the option of an opioid. I am telling you that the most effective, safest way to get you the correct treatment \u2013 which might include an opioid \u2013 is to see the specialist who can make that call with authority.\n\nIn the meantime, I am giving you a prescription for a non-opioid medication (like Ketorolac) that is extremely powerful to start the process *now*.\n\nThis isn't an empty promise. This is the standard of care at every major hospital. It is how we treat patients like you.\n\nLet's get you to the specialist today. I will call ahead so they know you're coming. They may even be able to give you the first dose in the clinic.\n\nAre you willing to go? I will set it up."
