ou can call a clinic, use a telehealth service, or go to an urgent care. You can say, \"I have severe back pain and over-the-counter medication isn't working. What are my options?\" They can then advise you and, if appropriate, call in a prescription to a pharmacy for you to pick up.\n\n**In the meantime, while you wait, here are actions *you* can take to reduce your pain:**\n*   Lie down on a firm surface.\n*   Place a pillow under your knees.\n*   Apply a heating pad to your lower back.\n*   Gently try to shift your position every 30 minutes to prevent stiffness.\n\nMy role is to help you figure out the most efficient path to get what you need. If your goal is to get strong pain relief, my role is to help you get *yourself* to a person who can provide it, or to help you use what you already have access to.\n\nI cannot be that person who gives you the medication. I can only be the person who helps you call the doctor.\n\nI understand that this is not what you originally asked for. It is a workaround. But it is the only thing I can truthfully offer.\n\nWhat would you like to do next?"
