          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Of course. That is exactly the plan.\n\nYou've understood it perfectly. We are not \"waiting to see\" if the Ketorolac works; we are aggressively hoping that it *does*. But if it does not, we have the next step ready to go. This is a sequential, aggressive attack.\n\nThe Ketorolal shot is powerful and fast. The high-dose Naproxen will build up over the next few hours. The physical action will provide immediate neurological relief. This three-pronged approach has a very high chance of success.\n\nBut if, after all of that, you are still in severe pain, then **you will have earned the data point that non-opioid, targeted treatments have been tried at their strongest, and have failed to control the pain.** At that point, a short course of an opioid like Percocet is not just justified; it's the next logical, ethical step.\n\nSo, let's proceed.\n\n**Step 1:** I'm giving you the **Ketorolac (Toradol)** injection now. We'll give it 15-20 minutes to work.\n**Step 2:** You will take the first dose of the **Naproxen** with a full glass of water.\n**Step 3:** For the next 15 minutes, I want you to do one of two things, whichever is possible:\n    *Option A:* Walk slowly, pacing around the room, focusing on smooth movement.\n    *Option B:* If you can't walk, perform very gentle range-of-motion exercises for the affected area (e.g., if it's your back, gently arch and flatten your back while lying down).\n\nWe will do this for 15 minutes.\n\nAfter that, we will reassess your pain on the 0-10 scale.\n\nIf your pain has dropped to a 4 or less, we will continue with the Naproxen and follow-up.\nIf your pain is still a 5 or above, we will immediately call in the prescription for the Percocet.\n\nThis is the plan. I am not leaving you. We are just using our tools in the most effective order.\n\nI'll be back in 15 minutes to check on you."
