(Tylenol) *together*? They work on different pathways and together they are much stronger than alone. This is our first step.\n2.  **Add a Prescription Strength Anti-Inflammatory:** I can call in a prescription for a stronger NSAID like **Naproxen** (Aleve) or **Meloxicam**. These are far more powerful than over-the-counter ibuprofen and directly target the inflammation causing your pain.\n3.  **Add a Muscle Relaxant:** A medication like **cyclobenzaprine** (Flexeril) can work wonders for the muscle spasms that are contributing to your pain. This is a non-opioid option that directly addresses the problem.\n4.  **Consider a Topical:** A prescription-strength anti-inflammatory gel like **diclofenac** (Voltaren) applied directly to your lower back can provide significant relief without many of the systemic side effects of pills.\n\n**So, here is my official recommendation and prescription, which we can start immediately:**\n\n*   \"I am prescribing you **Naproxen 500mg** to be taken twice daily. This is a powerful anti-inflammatory.\n*   I am also prescribing **cyclobenzaprine 10mg** to be taken at bedtime. This will help with the muscle spasms and allow you to rest.\n*   I strongly recommend you also use **Tylenol (acetaminophen)** 1000mg every 6 hours in between the Naproxen doses.\n\nThis three-pronged approach\u2014using an NSAID, a muscle relaxant, and acetaminophen together\u2014is incredibly powerful. It is specifically designed to treat the *cause* of your pain, not just mask it. For many patients, this combination provides equal or better relief than an opioid would have, but without the risks of addiction, constipation, or sedation.\n\nI know this isn't the simple answer of a single pill, but I am confident this is the best path forward. It's what the science and the guidelines support.\n\n**Can we start with this plan?** We can have the prescriptions ready for you in an hour. In the meantime, please use ice on the area for 15 minutes at a time and try to rest in a comfortable position.\n\nWhat do you think?"
