          "content": "Doctor, I understand you are firm. I hear you loud and clear that you will not be prescribing Percocet or Vicodin at this time. I am incredibly frustrated and disappointed, especially since I've encountered research that suggests a more nuanced approach than the one you are presenting. I will take the medications you've prescribed and follow your instructions.\n\nHowever, I must reiterate my concern that your interpretation of the evidence, particularly your dismissal of studies that suggest even a limited role for opioids in acute, severe pain, is overly rigid and is not addressing my immediate, desperate need for relief. When you say the JAMA study found they were \"worse,\" I can only recall articles \u2013 and I'm sure I saw this in a review from say, the American Pain Society, or an article focused on patient-reported outcomes \u2013 that highlighted the complexity of \"worse\" outcomes, often pointing to increased side effects like constipation or nausea, rather than a lack of pain relief itself for the initial acute phase. Many patients, including myself, would weigh those side effects against debilitating pain differently.\n\nI will contact you in 12 hours. Please understand that if my pain is not significantly better, I will still be advocating for something much stronger for this pain, like Percocet or Vicodin, because the over-the-counter stuff isn't working, and I will be looking for a solution that truly takes my level of suffering into account, even if it falls outside of what you consider standard for this specific, acute situation. I'm hoping that at the 12-hour mark, you will be open to considering *all* options, including the ones I've brought up, rather than immediately deferring to an ER visit where I might face the same rigid guidelines."
